\f0\fs24 \cf0 Cold glittered across the horizon, the setting sun casting long faces all across the city skyline. It would be another cold night, one far better left to the imagination\'97something Thomas Ginney had learned how to handle expertly. A mind that forgets when it is useful, and remembers only when it is absolutely necessary\'97or incentivised\'97is a survivor. He\'92d just returned from the soup kitchen to find a little girl going through his stash.
\f1 \

\f0 \'93Hey!\'94, he yelled as he increased his pace. The girl froze as if being gripped by the neck. Her face was dirty\'97the leftover marks of dried tears still on her cheeks. It wasn\'92t until Tom saw the terror in her eyes that he realised he\'92d raised his hand in anger. He quickly lowered it, and felt especially awful when he discovered the bright purple bruise on the girl\'92s left cheek.
\f1 \

\f0 \'93Don\'92t worry. I\'92m not going to hurt you.\'94 The girl stammered backwards\'97away from him\'97stepping into a trolley full of bags which scared her half to death.
\f1 \

\f0 Tom rummaged through his things and found a rather unpleasant looking orange. Although perfectly edible, it was very definitely amongst the things an untrained eye would have considered revolting. He\'92d salvaged it from a dumpster near the rear entrance of a high-society restaurant, where the clientele would be particularly accustomed to discarding imperfection.
\f1 \

\f0 \'93Here, take it.\'94 He stretched as best he could to reach the girl that was just as eager to take the orange as run away. They danced like this for a few feet until finally the orange came within her reach, at which point she immediately snatched it and ran.
\f1 \

\f0 Tom snorted, \'93there goes me breakfast. I suppose it\'92s for the best.\'94
\f1 \

\f0 \'93You\'92re too nice for this place, you know.\'94 Fred was sitting down with an extra piece of bread he\'92d nabbed from the kitchen, taking his time with it as best he could. He was quite obviously terrible at this.
\f1 \

\f0 \'93\'91s served me just fine, you\'92d do well to remember. Reckon that there kindness is the only reason I\'92m still around, after all. Long\'92s it been anyhow?\'94
\f1 \

\f0 Fred raised his shoulders at this, his mouth too full to speak as he\'92d taken the last few bites all at once.
\f1 \

\f0 \'93Yeh, what do you know, anyway,\'94 Tom snarked. The grin this caused on Fred\'92s face ejected crumbs all over his jacket, revealing a remarkably gapless row of teeth, that upon further inspection consisted largely of bread white.
\f1 \

\f0 Tom sat himself down and grabbed the first thing he could find from his stash. It was an unmarked bottle containing a brownish liquid he\'92d been given by some rather strange people, he thought. They hadn\'92t seemed particularly kind, to him\'97present evidence to the contrary. He opened the bottle and smelled it, winced and almost immediately smelled it again. He sipped it and waited.
\f1 \

\f0 \'93My god, this is pretty good.\'94 He sipped it again, his face contorting in ways his friends might have called considerate, but to most resembled a look of complete and utter disgust. The strong bite reminded Tom of younger vintages\'97he reckoned it hadn\'92t been an expensive gift\'97but the edge gave way to a taste that was unlike anything he would expect to find in poorly made whiskey.
\f1 \
